cussions with Secondary Headteachers have recommended that consideration is given to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e different challenges for rural and urban students from a white working class background. The impact of relative deprivation by comparison with the community you live with is distinct from being member of a community where a larger number are from a simil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ar social and economic context. This can be ,manifest in a more significant lack of aspiration and less experience of, and belief in,  the possibility and potential of social mobility. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.ii. School leaders felt that we do not know enough about the impac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t of social change on rural white working class learners. More needs to be done to understand the effect of changes in the ethnic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make-up of rural communities and the increased success and prosperity of young people form ethnic minority backgrounds. There </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a hypothesis that white working class communities  is a rural environment may be less well integrated into patterns of social change that are accepted in urban communities and, as a result, are less well equipped, and less positive about,  social or geo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">graphical mobility</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.6. We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> interviewed Headteachers from three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Aylesbury Primary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which serve less advantaged