-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.7.i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The importance of pastoral support was echoed by the secondary sector. Here it was argued that the achievement of all students from less advantaged backgrounds could be, and is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, enhanced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by an on-going, targeted, evidence based focus on removing barriers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">learning and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aspiration. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.7.ii. This would include a relentless focus on monitoring attendance, working in partnership with families, engaging with health professionals to support physical and mental health, with the police in targeting support for at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> risk students and promoting restorative justice. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.8 It is our view that those working in education from the earliest years to the end of the secondary phase need to work to engage with families and communities, to know the families in the communities th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ey serve and to build powerful relationships.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.9. It was felt that changes to the Ofsted framework over the last 18 months have reduced the significance and celebration of high quality pastoral care as a pre-requisite for student achievement, particularly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children and young people from less advantaged backgrounds.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether the problem is significantly worse for white working class boys than girls.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1. The data on FSM reflects the experience of schools that the issue is more pronounced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for boys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and gir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ls, but girls do, nonetheless, present cause for concern.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What steps schools can take to improve the educational outcomes and attainmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">t of white working class pupils?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1. We are supporting and promoting the interventions championed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the Sutton Trust, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Education Endowment fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Unseen Child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> report and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> supporting papers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These are a key element of our strategies to ensure Pupil Premium has an impact on standards and on narrowing the gap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for all underachieving groups</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2. We also believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that investing in good relationships with families and communities and strong pastoral care for children are key strategies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.3. We are convinced of the importance of early intervention and of coherent, joined up provision and collaboration between early</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> years, primary and secondary phases across communities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="f